I"H<p><a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/personalized-language-model-perplexity-approximates-surprisal">Personalized language model perplexity approximates surprisal</a>. Similar to flow and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/body-seeks-homeostasis">stress</a>, there is a sweet-spot of perplexity desired. Completely <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/forecasting-framing-renders-neural-emulation-feasible">predictable</a> <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/creative-output-can-support-educational-input-in-free-learning">resources</a> provide little value. Completely unpredictable resources are also not desired, as theyâ€™re not <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/good-learning-is-inherently-pleasurable">pleasant to digest</a>. Resources that are somewhat challenging but not <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/misogi-radically-modifies-affordances">impossible to tackle</a> should be <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/optimizing-for-short-semantic-distances-fosters-learning">aimed for</a>. This would lead to antifragile learning, an attitude of actively patching your weak spots and developing your thinking by systematically challenging yourself. The <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/ds-operates-best-at-the-edge-of-chaos">edge of chaos hypothesis</a> also supports this approach if keeping in mind <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/ds-can-be-entrained-by-input">entrainment</a> and <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/dreaming-exploits-idiosyncratic-neural-dynamics">the brain as a dynamical system</a>.</p>
